\begin_layout Title
Crime and Punishment: An Economic Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Albert Shyn Kwan Tan
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Basic Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Cost of Crime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Public and private expenditures are significantly understated, since expenditure
s by many public agencies in the course of enforcing particular piece of
 legislation and private precautions against crime are not included
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Due to large growth of tax and other legislation, tax evasion and other
 kinds of white-collar crime have presumably grow more rapidly than felonies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Indirect evidence of growth in crime is the large increase in the amount
 of currency circulation since 1929.
 Despite spread of credit cards and cheques, amount of currency used increases
 since using currency has no record of transactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amount of harm would tend to increase with activity level, as in the
 relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H & = & H(O)\\
\frac{dH}{dO} & > & 0\\
H_{i}" & > & 0\\
H & = & \text{Harm from crime}\\
O & = & \text{Crime activity level}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The social value gain to offenders,
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 also tend to increase with number of offenses
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
G & = & G(O)\\
G' & > & 0\\
G" & < & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The net cost or damage to the society by crime, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
D(O) & = & H(O)-G(O)\nonumber \\
D" & = & H"=G">0\label{eq:1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

It follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ref{eq:1})$
\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
D'(O)>O & \forall O>O_{a} & if\mbox{ \ensuremath{D'(O_{a})\geq0}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cost of murder measured by the lost of earnings of victims excludes
 the value society placed on life itself
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cost of gambling excludes the utility to those gambling and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

external
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 utility of some clergy and others
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cost of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 like burglars and embezzlement exclude social attitudes towards forced
 wealth redistribution and also the effects on capital accumulation of the
 possibility of theft
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Cost of Apprehension and Conviction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output of police and various court activity can be summarized as 
\begin_inset Formula $A=f(m,r,c)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the production summarizing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

state of arts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The cost of the activity, A can be summarized by the 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
C & = & C(A)\nonumber \\
C'(A) & > & 0\label{eq:2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

One approximation to an empirical measure of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

activity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the number of offenses clear by conviction.
 It can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
A & = & pO\label{eq:3}\\
p & = & \text{Probability that an offense is cleared by conviction}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

By (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"

\end_inset

), one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{p} & = & C'O>0\\
C_{o} & = & C'p>0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

An increase in either the probability of conviction and number of offenses
 would increase total cost.
 If marginal cost of increased activity is rising, further implications
 would be that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{pp} & = & C"O^{2}>0\\
C_{OO} & = & C"p^{2}>0\\
C_{pO} & = & C_{Op}=C"pO+C'>0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

A more sophisticated approach to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"

\end_inset

) is that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A & = & h(p,O,a)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 stands for the arrests and other determinants of activity and there is
 no presumption that the elasticity of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 equals that w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

.
 Substitution yields the cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $C=C(p,O,a)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Supply of Offenses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Person commits an offense if the expected utility to him exceeds the utility
 he could get by using his time and other resources at other activities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number of offense can be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
O & = & O(p,f,u)\\
\frac{dO}{dp} & < & 0\\
\frac{dO}{df} & < & 0\\
O & = & \text{Average market offense}\\
p & = & \text{Probability of getting convicted per offense}\\
f & = & \text{Punishment per offense}\\
u & = & \text{Portmanteau variable representing all other influences}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since only convicted offenders are punished, in effect there is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

price discrimination
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and uncertainty; if convicted, he pays 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 per convicted offense, while otherwise he does not
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The change in some component 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can be anticipated.
 For instance, a rise in the income available in legal activities or an
 increase in law-abiding due, say, to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

education
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would reduce the incentive to enter illegal activities, and thus number
 of offenses.
 Or a shift in the form of punishment from fine to imprisonment would reduce
 number of offenses since crime generally cannot be committed while in prison
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 compensated by an equal percentage reduction in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 would not change the expected income from an offense, but could change
 the expected utility, because the amount of risk would change.
 If individual is risk preferrers, increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (compensated by decrease in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

) would reduce number of offenses, and thus number of offenses; if the individua
l is risk averse, increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 would have a greater effect; if the individual is risk neutral, increase
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 have the same effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The widespread generalization that offenders are more deterred by the probabilit
y of conviction than punishment when convicted imply that offenders are
 risk preferrers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In equilibrium, real income of persons in risky activities are, at the margin,
 relative high or low as persons are generally risk avoiders or prefferers
 respectively
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Social loss from illegal activities is usually minimized by selecting 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in regions where risk is preferred i.e.
 regions where 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crime does not pay
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Punishments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cost of different punishments to an offender can be made comparable
 by converting into their monetary equivalent.
 For instance, the cost of imprisonment is the discounted sum of earnings
 forgone and the value placed in consumption and freedom.
 Hence, the cost of prison for an offender who can earn more outside is
 generally greater
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Punishments affect not only offenders but also other members of the society.
 Fines paid by offenders are received as revenue by others.
 At the same time, other members are hurt since imprisonment requires expenditur
e on guards, foods and etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Total social cost of punishments is the cost to offenders plus the cost
 or minus the gain to others
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The social costs can be written in terms of offender’s cost as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f' & = & bf\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f'$
\end_inset

 is the social cost and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient that transforms 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $f'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\thickapprox0$
\end_inset

 for fines, while 
\begin_inset Formula $b>1$
\end_inset

 for torture, probation, and imprisonment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimality Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 increases the social cost of offenses through its effect on the cost of
 combating offense, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 as does an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

 through the effect on the cost of punishments, 
\begin_inset Formula $bf$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not 1 and infinity respectively
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The social loss from offenses, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is defined as follow
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
L & = & D(O)+C(p,O)+bpfO\\
O & = & O(p,f)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The aim would be to select values of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 that minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $bpfO$
\end_inset

 is the total social loss from punishments, since 
\begin_inset Formula $bf$
\end_inset

 is the loss per offense punished and 
\begin_inset Formula $pO$
\end_inset

 is the number of offenses punished.
 Combining the FOC's, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
D'+C' & = & -bpf(1-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{f}})\label{eq:4}\\
D'+C'+C_{p}\frac{1}{O_{p}} & = & -bpf(1-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{p}})\label{eq:5}\\
\epsilon_{f} & = & -\frac{f}{O}O_{f}\nonumber \\
\epsilon_{p} & = & -\frac{p}{O}O_{p}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

