	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term on the left side of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"

\end_inset

) gives the marginal cost of increasing the number of offenses, O: in equation
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"

\end_inset

) through a reduction in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"

\end_inset

) through reduction in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C'>O$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be in a region where 
\begin_inset Formula $D'>0$
\end_inset

, the marginal cost of increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 must be positive.
 A reduction of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 partly reduces the cost of combating offenses, and, therefore the marginal
 cost of increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 must be less when 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is reduced; the former can even be negative if 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large.
 Average revenue, 
\begin_inset Formula $-bpf$
\end_inset

 is necessarily negative, but marginal revenue, give by RHS of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"

\end_inset

) is not necessary negative and would be positive if the elasticities 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{f}$
\end_inset

 were less than unity.
 Since the loss is minimized when marginal revenue equals marginal cost,
 the optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{f}$
\end_inset

 must be less than unity, and that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{p}$
\end_inset

 could only exceed unity if 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

 were sufficiently large.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the MC of changing 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 through change in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is less than that of changing 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, the equilibrium marginal revenue from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 must also be less than that of 
\begin_inset Formula $f.$
\end_inset

 But (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"

\end_inset

) indicate that marginal revenue from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 can be less iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{p}>\epsilon_{f}.$
\end_inset

 This is precisely the condition indicating offenders have the preference
 for risk and thus that crime does not pay.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The loss of offenses is minimized if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are selected from those regions where offenders, on balance, risk preferrers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the supply of depended only on 
\begin_inset Formula $pf$
\end_inset

-offenders are risk neutral- a reduction in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 compensated by an equal percentage increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 would leave 
\begin_inset Formula $pf,O,D(O),$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bpfO$
\end_inset

 unchanged but would reduce loss since the cost of apprehension and conviction
 would be lowered by reduction in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If offenders were risk avoiders, the loss would be minimized by setting
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 arbitrary close to 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Convicted criminal are punished in many countries rather severely, because
 an increased probability of conviction obviously absorbs public and private
 resources in the form of more policeman, judges and juries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Judges and juries may be unwilling to convict offenders if punishments are
 set very high
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Shifts in the Behavioral Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An increase in the marginal damage from a given number of offenses, 
\begin_inset Formula $D'$
\end_inset

, increases the marginal cost of changing offenses by a change in either
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The optimal number of offenses would necessarily decrease, because the
 optimal values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 would increase.
 In this case, optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 move in the same direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Crime and Punishment Graph2.jpg
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimal probability of apprehension and conviction and the punishment when
 conviction would be greater for more serious offense
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since an increase in marginal cost of apprehension, 
\begin_inset Formula $C'$
\end_inset

 has identical effects as an increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $D'$
\end_inset

, it must reduce the number of offenses.
 On the other hand, increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

 has no direct effect on the MC of changing offenses with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and reduces the cost of charging offenses by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 would decrease and only partially compensated with an increase 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, so that the optimal number of offenses go up.
 Accordingly, an increase in both 
\begin_inset Formula $C'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

 must increase the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 but can increase or decrease the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and number of offenses depending on the importance of 
\begin_inset Formula $C'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Although an improvement in technology and reform may or may not increase
 the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and reduce number of offenses but it does reduce 
\begin_inset Formula $f.$
\end_inset

 This explains why secular improvement in police technology and reform goes
 hand in hand with decline severity of punishments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The income of a firm would usually be larger if it could be separate, at
 little cost, its total market into sub markets that have substantially
 different elasticities of demand: higher prices would be charge in sub
 markets having lower elasticities.
 Similar, total market offenses could be separated into subs markets, where
 lower prices- lower 
\begin_inset Formula $p's$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f's$
\end_inset

 - is charged in less elastic sub markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Unpremeditated murderers are supposed to act impulsively, and therefore,
 to be relatively unresponsive to size of punishments; likewise, the insane
 or young are probably less affected by increase in the probability of convictio
n or the punishment when convicted.
 Hence, the relatively smaller prison terms and greater use of probation
 are used for such groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 increases the marginal revenue from changing the number of offenses by
 changing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 an thereby, increases the optimal number of offenses, reduces the optimal
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and increase the optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $p.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 would be smaller and optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 would be larger for punishment such as imprisonment relative to fines 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimality Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

, say, because punishment was by fine, and the cost of apprehending convicting
 offenders were also zero, the two optimality condition in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"

\end_inset

) would reduce to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
D'(O) & = & 0\\
G'(O) & = & H'(O)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The monetary value of penalties would equal to marginal harm caused by offenses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If marginal harm always exceed marginal gain, then the optimum level of
 crime is 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If cost of apprehension and convictions were not zero, then the optimality
 condition would have incorporate the marginal cost as well as marginal
 damages and would become, if probability of conviction is assumed to be
 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
D'(O)+C'(O,1) & = & 0\label{eq:6}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:6"

\end_inset

) would hold if the fine equaled the sum of marginal harm and marginal cost
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f & = & H'(O)+C'(O,1)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Offenders have to compensate for the cost of catching them as well as for
 the farm they directly do
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The case for fines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This subsection argues that fine should be used whenever feasible
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Probation and institutionalization used up social resources, and fines do
 not, since the latter are basically just transfer of payments, while the
 former use resources in form of prison fatalities and offender’s own time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is hard to determine the marginal gains and marginal harms of crimes,
 thus making it hard to determine the level of fine
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimal fines compensate victims and restore the status quo ex ante, so
 that victims are no worse off than if offenses were not committed.
 Not only do other punishments fail to compensate, but also require 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

victims
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to spend additional resources in carrying out punishment.
 Hence, there is additional punishment towards 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ex-convicts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

(people who went to jail) since they did not pay the debt to the society
 but there is no additional punishments for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ex-finees
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fines can be considered the price of an offense but so do any other form
 of offense; for example, the price of stealing a car is six month jail.
 The only difference is the measurement units
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimal fines should depend directly on social loss inflicted by the crime
 and not directly on offenders' income, race and etc 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Monetary value of a given fine is the same for all offenders but not the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a given sentence prison sentence or probation period is not; the latter
 is generally positively related to an offender's income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rich offenders are more likely to choose to pay fine instead of going to
 jail since cost of staying in prison is higher for them.
 On the other hand, poorer offenders have an incentive to choose jail over
 paying fine.
 This implication is that the probability of going to jail would be systematical
ly related to earnings of offenders: negatively for offenses punishable
 by imprisonment and positively for those punishable by fines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In certain cases where the harm exceeds the resource of offenders, other
 forms of punishment are required.
 Hence, crime like murder which is so heinous that no amount of money can
 compensate for are punished by lifetime imprisonment or capital punishment
